nism Displayed? Exhibitions and Museums of Communism in Poland -- tAbout the Authors -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do museums and cinema shape the image of the Communist past in today’s Central and Eastern Europe? This volume is the first systematic analysis of how visual techniques are used to understand and put into context the former regimes. After history “ended” in the Eastern Bloc in 1989, museums and other memorials mushroomed all over the region. These efforts tried both to explain the meaning of this lost history, as well as to shape public opinion on their society’s shared post-war heritage. Museums and films made political use of recollections of the recent past, and employed selected museum, memorial, and media tools and tactics to make its political intent historically credible. Thirteen essays from scholars around the region take a fresh look at the subject as they address the strategies of fashioning popular perceptions of the recent past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aCultural studies, Fascism, Film, Media, Memory in art, Memory politics, Museums, Postcommunism.1 aApor, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aApor, Péter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCristea, Gabriela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaković, Nevena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDominková, Petra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorváth, Zsolt K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMain, Izabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark, 